        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The goal of the proposed observations is to measure 
the polarization of the dust continuum emission down to the
intensity level of ~5 mJy/beam and allows us to probe the emission 
in a region that is already sufficiently distant from the central
source (and the base of the jet) to detect any change in the
polarization level and orientation.

Assuming a polarization fraction of 2%, the expected polarization 
signal is 100 muJy/beam at that position. In order to secure a 
SNR=5 detection, we thus need to obtain an rms of 20 muJy/beam in
the total intensity map. According to the OT, this can be achieved 
in 1.5h on-source integration time, corresponding to a total
observation time of 3.6h. This is larger that the minimum value 
of 3h that is needed to achieve sufficient parallactic angle coverage for calibration.

 </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The fixed frequency offered 
in Cycle 3 (centered on LO1 frequency at 343.5 GHz) is perfectly
matching our needs, as it is very close to the frequency that we observed in our
Cycle 0 project (continuum band centered on 341.5 GHz), making comparison with the existing maps straightforward.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to use the full polarization capabilities of ALMA in
Band 7, with an angular resolution of 0.4", similar to that of the
already available Cycle 0 data. On the map produced with these data, 
the continuum emission is extended over 2", wich is lower than one
third of the 12-m promary beam (18.4") at the requested frequency.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
