        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Increasing the resolution from that of our Cycle 0 data to 0.3", 
we consider the peak flux
will remain the same (40 mJy/beam) or will only slightly 
decrease, since the source has actually an estimated size of 0.3".
In order to keep a SNR similar to that of Cycle 0 data, we 
request an rms of 5 mJy/beam (with 488 kHz resolution). This 
will require 24 min on-source integration time, corresponding to 
1h total observing time.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>One spectral window of 234.375 MHz (209 km/s) is set on the HDO line, with a 
spectral resolution of 0.12 km/s
(that will be smoothed later to reach 0.43 km). The other three windows have been set on 
C17O(3-2), CO(3-2), and SiO(8-7), with the aim of mimicking our
Cycle 0 setup. These lines are much stronger than the HDO one. The C17O line, in
particular, will allow us to trace the C17O disk with an increased
angular resolution, disentanglying between keplerian rotation and the r^-1 trend (see Fig. 2).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The science goal is aimed at observing the HDO(313-422) line in the HH212 disk.
Our Cycle 0 data have revealed a very compact HDO source, with a fitted size of about
0.3 arcsec. The rms of these observations was 3 mJy/beam (0.11 K in a 
0.7x0.5" beam) with 0.43 km/s (488 kHz) resolution. The line peak is ~40 mJy/beam.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
