    <prp:code></prp:code>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to use the ALMA Cycle 3 polarisation capabilities to measure (and model) the magnetic field in the bright HH212 edge-on protostellar jet system and to image a tentative
HDO rotating disk. Our ALMA Cycle 0+1 Band 7 data revealed a spectacular picture, with all the crucial ingredients of the star-disk formation recipe. We imaged a fast jet (CO, 28SiO, 30SiO) opening low-velocity (C34S) cavities, and a C17O disk consistent with keplerian rotation out to 90 AU around a 0.3 Msun protostar.

We ask: (1) to image the dust polarisation in Band 7 at 0.4" scale to trace how the B-field varies from envelope to disk scales, and (2) to map the HDO emission at 0.3" to confirm/characterise (for the first time) the presence of a rotating disk around a Class 0 protostar. 

The requested observations will provide for the first time (to our knowledge) a comprehensive set of information on the relation between rotation, magnetic fields, and jets of a single (Class 0) protostar at the proposed spatial scales. We will compare the results with predictions for 3D MHD collapse simulations from our group to determine if the current scenario of magnetic braking during star-disk formation is valid.</prp:abstract>
